When the Confluence installer detected some modified file in the installation folder during the upgrade process, it does not clearly warn user to back up those file before proceeding with the upgrade. 

The upgrade process will overwrite the modified file in the installation folder therefore the file will not be recoverable if the user did not backup beforehand.

It is important to implement a *clear warning that the modified files will be overwritten*  during the upgrade process so users will  understand they need to backup their modified file on their own.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-32631].
  {panel}

Currently, the Confluence installer will only warn user regarding the existent of  modified file during the upgrade process. 

Some of the modified file might be important and if the user accidentally proceed with the upgrade before backup the file, those file will no longer be recoverable by normal means.

It would be good to automatically back up those file when detected before actually overwriting them in the upgrade process.

